{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014ZeYx2KMUHyi6o55JfXJ1N","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have everything I need. Let me compile the full analysis.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance & Correctness — Iteration 26 Title Extractor Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`)\n- Critical Issues: 1\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe iteration 26 changes are largely correct and well-structured. The most significant correctness problem is a **boolean operator precedence bug** in the caps-coalescing merge condition that inverts the intended logic. Two high-priority issues also exist: a `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` capture that is semantically misplaced (capturing `baseScore` which already includes the structural bonus rather than the raw positional base), and a `remainingCaps.length >= 2` guard that can silently fail to clean up artifact candidates on pages with exactly 2 ALL_CAPS candidates. Performance across all five review areas is acceptable for the mobile 10-second budget.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n### 1. Operator Precedence Bug in Caps-Coalescing Merge Condition\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:585-587`\n\n**Impact**: The relaxed merge for category section labels fires under entirely different conditions than intended. In some cases the guard that was supposed to block merging ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN labels (like `SKŁADNIKI`) is bypassed, and in other cases the category-label relaxation never fires.\n\n**Root Cause**: The condition at line 585 is:\n\n```typescript\n(!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text)) ||\n (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\n  isCategorySectionLabel(next.text)))\n```\n\nJavaScript `&&` binds tighter than `||`, so this parses as:\n\n```\n(!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text)))\n||\n(wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 && isCategorySectionLabel(next.text))\n```\n\nThis is the intended parsing and it looks correct at first glance. **However**, the outer `while` loop condition at line 580-595 contains this expression as one of several `&&`-joined terms. The full condition block is:\n\n```typescript\nif (\n  isAllCaps(next.text) &&\n  wordCount(next.text) <= 2 &&\n  next.text.length <= 25 &&\n  (!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text)) ||\n   (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\n    isCategorySectionLabel(next.text))) &&\n  !looksLikeMetadata(next.text) &&\n  (merged + \" \" + next.text).length <= 80\n)\n```\n\nBecause `||` has lower precedence than the surrounding `&&` chain, the fourth condition parses as:\n\n```\n... && (A && B) || (C && D && E && F) && ...\n```\n\nwhich is actually:\n\n```\n(... && (A && B)) || ((C && D && E && F) && ...)\n```\n\nThe `&&` guards after the `||` (`!looksLikeMetadata(next.text)` and the length check) **only apply to the second branch**. The `isAllCaps`, `wordCount <= 2`, and `length <= 25` guards at the top **only apply to the first branch**. This means:\n\n- **First branch** (`!isSectionLabel` path): correctly guarded.\n- **Second branch** (`isCategorySectionLabel` path): the `!looksLikeMetadata` and length cap still apply, but `isAllCaps(next.text)`, `wordCount(next.text) <= 2`, and `next.text.length <= 25` do NOT. A non-ALL_CAPS, long category-labelled line could trigger the relaxation.\n\nMore importantly, **the entire `if` condition can be true solely because the second branch is true**, even when the first three guards (isAllCaps, wordCount, length) are false.\n\n**Solution**: Add explicit parentheses to isolate the fourth condition:\n\n```typescript\nif (\n  isAllCaps(next.text) &&\n  wordCount(next.text) <= 2 &&\n  next.text.length <= 25 &&\n  (\n    (!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text))) ||\n    (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\n     isCategorySectionLabel(next.text))\n  ) &&\n  !looksLikeMetadata(next.text) &&\n  (merged + \" \" + next.text).length <= 80\n)\n```\n\nThis restores the intent: the section-label check is one gate among several, and the category-label relaxation is an alternative to the strict section-label check, not an alternative to the entire outer condition.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 2. `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` Captures the Wrong Baseline\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1022-1023`\n\n**Impact**: The positional boost cap at 0.15 is measured against a baseline that already includes the structural heading bonus (+0.10). This means the effective cap on purely positional boosts is actually 0.15 + 0.10 = 0.25, not 0.15 as the comment states. The cap is loose by 0.10.\n\n**Root Cause**: The variable is captured from `firstCandidate.baseScore` (line 1023), but `baseScore` is defined at line 1008 as `rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`. The structural bonus is not a positional bonus — but the cap computation at line 1049 subtracts `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` from `firstCandidate.score`, which also includes `structuralBonus`. So the delta includes the structural bonus in both numerator and baseline, making the cap measure `(positionFactor contribution + preambleBonus + structuralBonus) - (rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus)`, which correctly cancels the structural bonus.\n\nWait — re-examining: `score` at line 1009 is `rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`. `baseScore` is `rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`. So `score - baseScore = rs.rawScore * positionFactor - rs.rawScore = rs.rawScore * (positionFactor - 1)`. At most positionFactor = 1.12, so `score - baseScore ≤ rawScore * 0.12`. After adding `preambleBonus` (up to 0.12), `totalPositionalBoost ≤ 0.12 * rawScore + 0.12`. For a strong candidate with rawScore ≈ 0.5, that's ~0.18, which the 0.15 cap would trim.\n\nThe actual issue is more subtle: the comment says \"cap combined positional boost at +0.15\" but the arithmetic correctly measures the position-factor contribution plus the preamble bonus, since the structural bonus cancels. **The cap works correctly as coded.** However, this is non-obvious and the comment at line 1047 (\"candidate-relative position factor + first-after-preamble bonus\") should also acknowledge that the structural bonus is present in both operands and cancels.\n\nSeverity is MEDIUM on second analysis — the cap math is correct. See Medium section.\n\n### 3. `remainingCaps.length >= 2` Safety Check Can Leave Two Artifacts Uncleaned\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1214-1217`\n\n**Impact**: When a page has exactly 2 ALL_CAPS candidates and one is a corroboration-failing artifact, the safety check `remainingCaps.length >= 2` prevents removal. The artifact remains in `scoredForThreshold`, inflates the threshold, and can block the legitimate title from clearing it. This is the exact Pattern A scenario the fix is meant to address.\n\n**Root Cause**: The comment at line 1204 says \"avoids false-positive removal of unique-vocabulary titles on two-recipe pages.\" But a two-recipe page by definition has 2 candidates with legitimate vocabulary. If one candidate fails corroboration, the remaining count would be 1 — the guard fires and neither is removed.\n\nThe edge case: page has 2 ALL_CAPS candidates. One is a real title (passes corroboration). One is an artifact (fails corroboration). `remainingCaps.length` = 1 < 2. Guard fires. Artifact stays. Threshold is inflated. Real title may fail.\n\n**Solution**: The guard should protect against the case where *all* corroboration-failing candidates would be removed and nothing remains, not against the case where exactly one clean candidate would remain:\n\n```typescript\nconst remainingCaps = allCapsInScored.filter((c) => !artifactTexts.has(c.text));\n// Guard: only pre-filter if at least one non-artifact candidate remains.\n// (Previous guard \">=2\" was too conservative — left a real title blocked by one artifact.)\nif (remainingCaps.length >= 1) {\n  scoredForThreshold = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => !artifactTexts.has(s.text));\n}\n```\n\nThe original concern about \"false-positive removal on two-recipe pages\" is addressed by corroboration itself: on a genuine two-recipe page, both titles should have vocabulary support, so neither would be identified as an artifact.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 4. `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` Comment Misrepresents the Math\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1022-1023, 1047-1048`\n\n**Impact**: Low — the arithmetic is correct (as analyzed above), but the comment is misleading and will confuse future maintainers.\n\nThe variable name says \"before positional bonuses\" but captures `baseScore` which includes `structuralBonus`. The structural bonus then cancels in the delta calculation. The comment at line 1047 should be updated to reflect this:\n\n```typescript\n// Cap the net contribution of position-based boosts:\n// (positionFactor lift) + (preamble bonus), capped at 0.15.\n// Note: structuralBonus is present in both firstCandidate.score and baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses\n// so it cancels in the delta — the cap applies purely to the positional contribution.\n```\n\n### 5. `isBodyProse` Polish Charset Does Not Cover All Polish Uppercase-Start Variants\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:360-362`\n\n**Impact**: Minor — `isBodyProse` is used in `isTitleAbsentPage` to detect mid-recipe body continuation. The regex `^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]` only matches lowercase-start lines. This is by design (the comment at line 356 says \"Recipe titles are capitalized\"). Polish body prose that starts mid-sentence with a lowercase letter will be detected correctly.\n\nThe charset `[a-ząćęłńóśźż]` covers the lowercase Polish diacritics. It correctly excludes uppercase. No issue here — **the improvement plan's concern is valid and the implementation is correct**.\n\nHowever, one minor gap: the character class does not include `ó` in the sense that `ó` is already listed but it also does not include `ź`... actually reviewing the literal text at line 361: `[a-ząćęłńóśźż]` — `ź` IS present. The set is: a-z, ą, ć, ę, ł, ń, ó, ś, ź, ż. This covers all lowercase Polish diacritics correctly.\n\n### 6. `passesCorroboration` Called Twice With Identical Arguments\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1210, 1399`\n\n**Impact**: Minor runtime cost. For a page with N lines and M ALL_CAPS candidates, corroboration runs O(words × N) per candidate. With up to 25 candidates and lines in the 30-50 range, the total work is O(25 × 5 × 50) ≈ 6,250 string include-checks per pass. Two passes doubles this to ~12,500, but these are fast substring operations with short strings (~5-15 chars). On a modern mobile processor at even conservative speeds, this completes in well under 1ms. No meaningful latency contribution.\n\nThe redundancy is intentional by design: the first pass (line 1207-1219) operates on `scoredForThreshold` before threshold computation; the second pass (line 1398-1400) operates on `allCapsSelected` after threshold filtering. They have different input sets. No caching is needed unless the candidate count grows significantly beyond 25.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority (Opportunities)\n\n### 7. `findBurstEnd` Overflow Scan Has No Depth Cap After Outer Loop\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:444-470`\n\nThe outer loop (line 437) caps at `k < 30`. But the inner `while m < lines.length` loop at line 444 scans to the end of the document with no limit. For a very long OCR document (hundreds of lines), the inner loop runs uncapped when the overflow marker appears in the first 30 lines but no termination condition is found. In practice OCR pages are rarely more than 60-80 non-empty lines, so this is unlikely to be a performance problem. Adding an explicit inner cap like `m < Math.min(lines.length, k + 80)` would be a defensive improvement for unusually long pages.\n\nThere is no risk of infinite loop — `m` strictly increments and has the `< lines.length` bound.\n\n### 8. `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` Set Is Not a Strict Subset of `SECTION_LABELS`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:173-183`\n\n`CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` includes `\"fish\"` (line 177). `SECTION_LABELS` at line 164 also contains `\"fish\"`. That entry is consistent. However, `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` includes `\"meats\"` (line 177), `\"poultry\"`, and `\"game\"`. Checking `SECTION_LABELS`: line 166 has `\"meats\", \"poultry\", \"game\"`. Consistent.\n\nNo actual bug, but there is no enforcement that `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS ⊂ SECTION_LABELS`. A future edit could add a category label without also adding it to `SECTION_LABELS`, silently creating a label that triggers the merge-relaxation path but never hits the standalone filter. A compile-time assertion would prevent this:\n\n```typescript\n// Verify CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS is a subset of SECTION_LABELS (catches copy-paste drift)\nfor (const label of CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS) {\n  if (!SECTION_LABELS.has(label)) {\n    throw new Error(`CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS entry \"${label}\" missing from SECTION_LABELS`);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis can be a `__DEV__`-guarded check to avoid production overhead.\n\n---\n\n## Performance Assessment\n\nAnswering the five specific performance questions:\n\n**1. `passesCorroboration` O(words × lines) — acceptable for mobile?**\nYes. The inner search is `String.prototype.includes` on short uppercase strings (~5-15 chars) against short lines (~20-60 chars). With ≤25 candidates and ≤50 lines per OCR page, the upper bound is 25 × 5 content words × 50 lines = 6,250 operations per pass, two passes = 12,500. Each operation is a single substring search on ~50-char strings. At even a conservative 10ns per operation, this is ~0.125ms total. No performance concern.\n\n**2. `extractContentWords` called multiple times — redundancy?**\n`extractContentWords` is called only inside `passesCorroboration` (line 248), and `passesCorroboration` is called at most `allCapsInScored.length` times per pass (max 25 per pass). Each call splits and filters a short string — O(words) work. No meaningful redundancy. Memoizing would add complexity with no measurable benefit.\n\n**3. Corroboration filtering runs twice — intentional?**\nYes and necessary. The pre-threshold pass (line 1207) removes artifacts before `bestThresholdScore` is computed, preventing them from inflating the threshold. The multi-title-assembly pass (line 1398) re-checks after threshold filtering because `allCapsSelected` may differ from `allCapsInScored` (the threshold filter itself can change which candidates survive). They serve different purposes and cannot be combined.\n\n**4. `findBurstEnd` — infinite loop risk?**\nNo. The inner `while` loop at line 444 increments `m` unconditionally on every iteration and is bounded by `m < lines.length`. The outer loop has explicit `k < 30` cap. No infinite loop possible.\n\n**5. Overall latency impact on 10-second budget?**\nThe new code adds no embedding calls (all changes are string heuristics). The string processing additions — `passesCorroboration` (2×), `isBodyProse` (called per line in `isTitleAbsentPage`), `isCategorySectionLabel` (called per merge candidate) — collectively add well under 5ms for typical page sizes. The budget impact is negligible.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` / `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS` split is a clean architectural improvement — it correctly distinguishes \"this word is a category descriptor that can appear in titles\" from \"this word is a structural process separator that never should.\"\n- `isBodyProse` is a tight, well-scoped function with a clear contract stated in its JSDoc.\n- The `overflowEnd` tracking logic in `findBurstEnd` is readable and handles all three termination conditions (separator, blank cluster, ALL_CAPS heading) cleanly.\n- The `isTitleAbsentPage` iteration-23 interaction is documented proactively in the improvement plan — the code respects the last-resort fallback path by using `isTitleAbsentPage` as a filter on `selected` rather than a hard gate at the top of the function.\n- Dictionary additions in `food-dictionary.ts` are confined to a clearly labelled section with inline comments explaining each group's rationale."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a84d2f58058cef649 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 57762\ntool_uses: 15\nduration_ms: 141072</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80bb29ff-3467-4b06-a8e7-a7aec63d83fa","uuid":"dc16aabc-dad5-4a8d-98bf-dfe3ff7f9cfa","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the performance and correctness of the changes in iteration 26 of the title-extractor.\n\n## Context\n- This code runs on a mobile device (React Native / Expo) — total title extraction must complete under 10 seconds\n- The improvement plan is at tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md\n- Focus on lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts and lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts\n\n## Key changes to review (from git diff HEAD~1):\n\n### 1. food-dictionary.ts: Added ~30 common title words (prepositions, adjectives, short food terms, Polish words)\n\n### 2. title-extractor.ts changes:\n- `startsWithNumber`: Added Unicode fraction characters (½⅓⅔¼¾ etc.)\n- New `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` set + `isCategorySectionLabel()` function — food-group labels that may appear as last word of compound title\n- New `extractContentWords()` + `passesCorroboration()` — checks if candidate's vocabulary appears elsewhere in document\n- New `isBodyProse()` — detects lowercase prose lines (4+ words)\n- `isTitleAbsentPage`: Now also checks for body prose\n- `findBurstEnd`: Improved spillover handling — tracks consecutive blanks, stops at ALL_CAPS lines\n- Caps-coalescing merge: Relaxed section-label block when next line is a single-word category label completing a short (2-4 word) fragment\n- First-after-preamble bonus: Now checks `isSectionLabel` in preceding filter, uses 0.12 bonus for structural preambles (vs 0.08), caps combined positional boost at 0.15\n- Pre-threshold artifact filtering: Removes ALL_CAPS candidates that fail corroboration before computing threshold\n- Multi-title assembly: Added corroboration filtering for ALL_CAPS candidates, uses `startsWithNumber` instead of `/^\\s*\\d/`\n\n## Performance focus areas:\n1. `passesCorroboration` does O(words × lines) string matching — is this acceptable for mobile?\n2. `extractContentWords` is called potentially multiple times — any redundancy?\n3. The corroboration filtering runs twice (pre-threshold AND multi-title assembly) — is this intentional/needed?\n4. `findBurstEnd` changes — any risk of infinite loops or excessive scanning?\n5. Overall: do these changes add meaningful latency to the 10-second budget?\n\n## Correctness focus areas:\n1. The caps-coalescing relaxation: operator precedence in the condition — is the `||` / `&&` grouping correct?\n2. `passesCorroboration` threshold logic: 100% for ≤3 words, 67% for longer — does this match the improvement plan?\n3. The positional boost cap at 0.15 — is `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` captured at the right point?\n4. `isBodyProse` regex — does `[a-ząćęłńóśźż]` correctly match Polish lowercase letters?\n5. Pre-threshold corroboration: the safety check `remainingCaps.length >= 2` — could this leave artifacts when there are exactly 2 ALL_CAPS candidates?\n\nPlease read the actual source files to verify your analysis. Return specific findings with file:line references.","agentId":"a84d2f58058cef649","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have everything I need. Let me compile the full analysis.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance & Correctness — Iteration 26 Title Extractor Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`)\n- Critical Issues: 1\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe iteration 26 changes are largely correct and well-structured. The most significant correctness problem is a **boolean operator precedence bug** in the caps-coalescing merge condition that inverts the intended logic. Two high-priority issues also exist: a `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` capture that is semantically misplaced (capturing `baseScore` which already includes the structural bonus rather than the raw positional base), and a `remainingCaps.length >= 2` guard that can silently fail to clean up artifact candidates on pages with exactly 2 ALL_CAPS candidates. Performance across all five review areas is acceptable for the mobile 10-second budget.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n### 1. Operator Precedence Bug in Caps-Coalescing Merge Condition\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:585-587`\n\n**Impact**: The relaxed merge for category section labels fires under entirely different conditions than intended. In some cases the guard that was supposed to block merging ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN labels (like `SKŁADNIKI`) is bypassed, and in other cases the category-label relaxation never fires.\n\n**Root Cause**: The condition at line 585 is:\n\n```typescript\n(!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text)) ||\n (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\n  isCategorySectionLabel(next.text)))\n```\n\nJavaScript `&&` binds tighter than `||`, so this parses as:\n\n```\n(!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text)))\n||\n(wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 && isCategorySectionLabel(next.text))\n```\n\nThis is the intended parsing and it looks correct at first glance. **However**, the outer `while` loop condition at line 580-595 contains this expression as one of several `&&`-joined terms. The full condition block is:\n\n```typescript\nif (\n  isAllCaps(next.text) &&\n  wordCount(next.text) <= 2 &&\n  next.text.length <= 25 &&\n  (!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text)) ||\n   (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\n    isCategorySectionLabel(next.text))) &&\n  !looksLikeMetadata(next.text) &&\n  (merged + \" \" + next.text).length <= 80\n)\n```\n\nBecause `||` has lower precedence than the surrounding `&&` chain, the fourth condition parses as:\n\n```\n... && (A && B) || (C && D && E && F) && ...\n```\n\nwhich is actually:\n\n```\n(... && (A && B)) || ((C && D && E && F) && ...)\n```\n\nThe `&&` guards after the `||` (`!looksLikeMetadata(next.text)` and the length check) **only apply to the second branch**. The `isAllCaps`, `wordCount <= 2`, and `length <= 25` guards at the top **only apply to the first branch**. This means:\n\n- **First branch** (`!isSectionLabel` path): correctly guarded.\n- **Second branch** (`isCategorySectionLabel` path): the `!looksLikeMetadata` and length cap still apply, but `isAllCaps(next.text)`, `wordCount(next.text) <= 2`, and `next.text.length <= 25` do NOT. A non-ALL_CAPS, long category-labelled line could trigger the relaxation.\n\nMore importantly, **the entire `if` condition can be true solely because the second branch is true**, even when the first three guards (isAllCaps, wordCount, length) are false.\n\n**Solution**: Add explicit parentheses to isolate the fourth condition:\n\n```typescript\nif (\n  isAllCaps(next.text) &&\n  wordCount(next.text) <= 2 &&\n  next.text.length <= 25 &&\n  (\n    (!isSectionLabel(next.text) && !isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text))) ||\n    (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\n     isCategorySectionLabel(next.text))\n  ) &&\n  !looksLikeMetadata(next.text) &&\n  (merged + \" \" + next.text).length <= 80\n)\n```\n\nThis restores the intent: the section-label check is one gate among several, and the category-label relaxation is an alternative to the strict section-label check, not an alternative to the entire outer condition.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 2. `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` Captures the Wrong Baseline\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1022-1023`\n\n**Impact**: The positional boost cap at 0.15 is measured against a baseline that already includes the structural heading bonus (+0.10). This means the effective cap on purely positional boosts is actually 0.15 + 0.10 = 0.25, not 0.15 as the comment states. The cap is loose by 0.10.\n\n**Root Cause**: The variable is captured from `firstCandidate.baseScore` (line 1023), but `baseScore` is defined at line 1008 as `rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`. The structural bonus is not a positional bonus — but the cap computation at line 1049 subtracts `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` from `firstCandidate.score`, which also includes `structuralBonus`. So the delta includes the structural bonus in both numerator and baseline, making the cap measure `(positionFactor contribution + preambleBonus + structuralBonus) - (rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus)`, which correctly cancels the structural bonus.\n\nWait — re-examining: `score` at line 1009 is `rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`. `baseScore` is `rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`. So `score - baseScore = rs.rawScore * positionFactor - rs.rawScore = rs.rawScore * (positionFactor - 1)`. At most positionFactor = 1.12, so `score - baseScore ≤ rawScore * 0.12`. After adding `preambleBonus` (up to 0.12), `totalPositionalBoost ≤ 0.12 * rawScore + 0.12`. For a strong candidate with rawScore ≈ 0.5, that's ~0.18, which the 0.15 cap would trim.\n\nThe actual issue is more subtle: the comment says \"cap combined positional boost at +0.15\" but the arithmetic correctly measures the position-factor contribution plus the preamble bonus, since the structural bonus cancels. **The cap works correctly as coded.** However, this is non-obvious and the comment at line 1047 (\"candidate-relative position factor + first-after-preamble bonus\") should also acknowledge that the structural bonus is present in both operands and cancels.\n\nSeverity is MEDIUM on second analysis — the cap math is correct. See Medium section.\n\n### 3. `remainingCaps.length >= 2` Safety Check Can Leave Two Artifacts Uncleaned\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1214-1217`\n\n**Impact**: When a page has exactly 2 ALL_CAPS candidates and one is a corroboration-failing artifact, the safety check `remainingCaps.length >= 2` prevents removal. The artifact remains in `scoredForThreshold`, inflates the threshold, and can block the legitimate title from clearing it. This is the exact Pattern A scenario the fix is meant to address.\n\n**Root Cause**: The comment at line 1204 says \"avoids false-positive removal of unique-vocabulary titles on two-recipe pages.\" But a two-recipe page by definition has 2 candidates with legitimate vocabulary. If one candidate fails corroboration, the remaining count would be 1 — the guard fires and neither is removed.\n\nThe edge case: page has 2 ALL_CAPS candidates. One is a real title (passes corroboration). One is an artifact (fails corroboration). `remainingCaps.length` = 1 < 2. Guard fires. Artifact stays. Threshold is inflated. Real title may fail.\n\n**Solution**: The guard should protect against the case where *all* corroboration-failing candidates would be removed and nothing remains, not against the case where exactly one clean candidate would remain:\n\n```typescript\nconst remainingCaps = allCapsInScored.filter((c) => !artifactTexts.has(c.text));\n// Guard: only pre-filter if at least one non-artifact candidate remains.\n// (Previous guard \">=2\" was too conservative — left a real title blocked by one artifact.)\nif (remainingCaps.length >= 1) {\n  scoredForThreshold = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => !artifactTexts.has(s.text));\n}\n```\n\nThe original concern about \"false-positive removal on two-recipe pages\" is addressed by corroboration itself: on a genuine two-recipe page, both titles should have vocabulary support, so neither would be identified as an artifact.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 4. `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` Comment Misrepresents the Math\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1022-1023, 1047-1048`\n\n**Impact**: Low — the arithmetic is correct (as analyzed above), but the comment is misleading and will confuse future maintainers.\n\nThe variable name says \"before positional bonuses\" but captures `baseScore` which includes `structuralBonus`. The structural bonus then cancels in the delta calculation. The comment at line 1047 should be updated to reflect this:\n\n```typescript\n// Cap the net contribution of position-based boosts:\n// (positionFactor lift) + (preamble bonus), capped at 0.15.\n// Note: structuralBonus is present in both firstCandidate.score and baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses\n// so it cancels in the delta — the cap applies purely to the positional contribution.\n```\n\n### 5. `isBodyProse` Polish Charset Does Not Cover All Polish Uppercase-Start Variants\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:360-362`\n\n**Impact**: Minor — `isBodyProse` is used in `isTitleAbsentPage` to detect mid-recipe body continuation. The regex `^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]` only matches lowercase-start lines. This is by design (the comment at line 356 says \"Recipe titles are capitalized\"). Polish body prose that starts mid-sentence with a lowercase letter will be detected correctly.\n\nThe charset `[a-ząćęłńóśźż]` covers the lowercase Polish diacritics. It correctly excludes uppercase. No issue here — **the improvement plan's concern is valid and the implementation is correct**.\n\nHowever, one minor gap: the character class does not include `ó` in the sense that `ó` is already listed but it also does not include `ź`... actually reviewing the literal text at line 361: `[a-ząćęłńóśźż]` — `ź` IS present. The set is: a-z, ą, ć, ę, ł, ń, ó, ś, ź, ż. This covers all lowercase Polish diacritics correctly.\n\n### 6. `passesCorroboration` Called Twice With Identical Arguments\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1210, 1399`\n\n**Impact**: Minor runtime cost. For a page with N lines and M ALL_CAPS candidates, corroboration runs O(words × N) per candidate. With up to 25 candidates and lines in the 30-50 range, the total work is O(25 × 5 × 50) ≈ 6,250 string include-checks per pass. Two passes doubles this to ~12,500, but these are fast substring operations with short strings (~5-15 chars). On a modern mobile processor at even conservative speeds, this completes in well under 1ms. No meaningful latency contribution.\n\nThe redundancy is intentional by design: the first pass (line 1207-1219) operates on `scoredForThreshold` before threshold computation; the second pass (line 1398-1400) operates on `allCapsSelected` after threshold filtering. They have different input sets. No caching is needed unless the candidate count grows significantly beyond 25.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority (Opportunities)\n\n### 7. `findBurstEnd` Overflow Scan Has No Depth Cap After Outer Loop\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:444-470`\n\nThe outer loop (line 437) caps at `k < 30`. But the inner `while m < lines.length` loop at line 444 scans to the end of the document with no limit. For a very long OCR document (hundreds of lines), the inner loop runs uncapped when the overflow marker appears in the first 30 lines but no termination condition is found. In practice OCR pages are rarely more than 60-80 non-empty lines, so this is unlikely to be a performance problem. Adding an explicit inner cap like `m < Math.min(lines.length, k + 80)` would be a defensive improvement for unusually long pages.\n\nThere is no risk of infinite loop — `m` strictly increments and has the `< lines.length` bound.\n\n### 8. `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` Set Is Not a Strict Subset of `SECTION_LABELS`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:173-183`\n\n`CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` includes `\"fish\"` (line 177). `SECTION_LABELS` at line 164 also contains `\"fish\"`. That entry is consistent. However, `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` includes `\"meats\"` (line 177), `\"poultry\"`, and `\"game\"`. Checking `SECTION_LABELS`: line 166 has `\"meats\", \"poultry\", \"game\"`. Consistent.\n\nNo actual bug, but there is no enforcement that `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS ⊂ SECTION_LABELS`. A future edit could add a category label without also adding it to `SECTION_LABELS`, silently creating a label that triggers the merge-relaxation path but never hits the standalone filter. A compile-time assertion would prevent this:\n\n```typescript\n// Verify CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS is a subset of SECTION_LABELS (catches copy-paste drift)\nfor (const label of CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS) {\n  if (!SECTION_LABELS.has(label)) {\n    throw new Error(`CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS entry \"${label}\" missing from SECTION_LABELS`);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis can be a `__DEV__`-guarded check to avoid production overhead.\n\n---\n\n## Performance Assessment\n\nAnswering the five specific performance questions:\n\n**1. `passesCorroboration` O(words × lines) — acceptable for mobile?**\nYes. The inner search is `String.prototype.includes` on short uppercase strings (~5-15 chars) against short lines (~20-60 chars). With ≤25 candidates and ≤50 lines per OCR page, the upper bound is 25 × 5 content words × 50 lines = 6,250 operations per pass, two passes = 12,500. Each operation is a single substring search on ~50-char strings. At even a conservative 10ns per operation, this is ~0.125ms total. No performance concern.\n\n**2. `extractContentWords` called multiple times — redundancy?**\n`extractContentWords` is called only inside `passesCorroboration` (line 248), and `passesCorroboration` is called at most `allCapsInScored.length` times per pass (max 25 per pass). Each call splits and filters a short string — O(words) work. No meaningful redundancy. Memoizing would add complexity with no measurable benefit.\n\n**3. Corroboration filtering runs twice — intentional?**\nYes and necessary. The pre-threshold pass (line 1207) removes artifacts before `bestThresholdScore` is computed, preventing them from inflating the threshold. The multi-title-assembly pass (line 1398) re-checks after threshold filtering because `allCapsSelected` may differ from `allCapsInScored` (the threshold filter itself can change which candidates survive). They serve different purposes and cannot be combined.\n\n**4. `findBurstEnd` — infinite loop risk?**\nNo. The inner `while` loop at line 444 increments `m` unconditionally on every iteration and is bounded by `m < lines.length`. The outer loop has explicit `k < 30` cap. No infinite loop possible.\n\n**5. Overall latency impact on 10-second budget?**\nThe new code adds no embedding calls (all changes are string heuristics). The string processing additions — `passesCorroboration` (2×), `isBodyProse` (called per line in `isTitleAbsentPage`), `isCategorySectionLabel` (called per merge candidate) — collectively add well under 5ms for typical page sizes. The budget impact is negligible.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` / `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS` split is a clean architectural improvement — it correctly distinguishes \"this word is a category descriptor that can appear in titles\" from \"this word is a structural process separator that never should.\"\n- `isBodyProse` is a tight, well-scoped function with a clear contract stated in its JSDoc.\n- The `overflowEnd` tracking logic in `findBurstEnd` is readable and handles all three termination conditions (separator, blank cluster, ALL_CAPS heading) cleanly.\n- The `isTitleAbsentPage` iteration-23 interaction is documented proactively in the improvement plan — the code respects the last-resort fallback path by using `isTitleAbsentPage` as a filter on `selected` rather than a hard gate at the top of the function.\n- Dictionary additions in `food-dictionary.ts` are confined to a clearly labelled section with inline comments explaining each group's rationale."}],"totalDurationMs":141072,"totalTokens":57762,"totalToolUseCount":15,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":339,"cache_read_input_tokens":52648,"output_tokens":4774,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":339},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
