{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HaHJoE3M7oWYD8GwitwFDo","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. Here is the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Title Extractor — Iteration 26 Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`)\n- Plan Coverage: 5 of 6 planned changes implemented; 1 partially implemented; 1 added beyond plan\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Low Priority / Style: 3\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAll five root-cause fixes from the improvement plan were implemented, with Fix 4 (first-after-preamble bonus) implemented more completely than planned thanks to the addition of the +0.15 cap. One significant change was added beyond the plan: the pre-threshold artifact filter using `passesCorroboration` (lines 1206–1219), which is a meaningful new behaviour that the plan explicitly marked as \"no changes to multi-title assembly logic.\" The three-set label taxonomy (`SECTION_LABELS` / `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` / `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS`) now governs the same labels from three directions, and the relationships between them are not enforced in code. This is the main structural risk.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` is manually maintained and can silently drift from `SECTION_LABELS`\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:173–183`\n\n`CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` is a hand-curated subset of the category labels inside `SECTION_LABELS`. Three sets now describe overlapping membership for the same labels:\n\n```\nSECTION_LABELS            — authoritative list of all labels\nCATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS   — subset: food-group/chapter labels only\nALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS  — subset: structural process labels only\n```\n\nThe plan asks \"should `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` be derived from `SECTION_LABELS`?\" and the answer in the code is: no, it was typed out again. Concretely:\n\n- `\"main courses\"`, `\"side dishes\"`, `\"soups & broths\"`, `\"desserts & baked goods\"`, `\"fish & seafood\"`, and `\"baked goods\"` are in `SECTION_LABELS` (line 162–166) but absent from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`.\n- `\"przetwory\"` is in `SECTION_LABELS` (line 154) but missing from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`.\n- `\"dania glowne\"` is in `SECTION_LABELS` (line 151) and absent from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` — yet its English equivalent `\"main courses\"` is also absent.\n\nIf a new category label is added to `SECTION_LABELS` it will silently fail the merge-relaxation check in the caps-coalescing loop, because `isCategorySectionLabel` only consults its own independent set.\n\n**Root cause**: The three sets should form a partition of `SECTION_LABELS`, but there is no code to enforce that. The comment at line 169–172 documents the intent but does not implement it.\n\n**Solution** — derive `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` from `SECTION_LABELS` by exclusion:\n\n```typescript\n// Structural process labels that always block merges\nconst ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS = new Set([\n  \"ingredients\", \"directions\", /* ... */\n]);\n\n// Everything in SECTION_LABELS that isn't a process label is a category label\nconst CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS = new Set(\n  [...SECTION_LABELS].filter((label) => !ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS.has(label))\n);\n```\n\nThis makes the partition explicit. The only tricky entries are the cross-over ones — `\"sos\"`, `\"ciasto\"`, `\"nadzienie\"` appear in both `SECTION_LABELS` (as structural, line 127–128) and `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS` (line 213). If you derive `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` by exclusion, those correctly end up not in the category set, which matches the intent.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `passesCorroboration` is called twice on overlapping populations — caching is absent\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1210` and `1399`\n\nThe function is called once in the pre-threshold artifact filter (lines 1206–1219) over `allCapsInScored` (which is a filtered view of `scoredForThreshold`), and again inside the multi-title assembly path (lines 1398–1400) over `allCapsSelected` (a filtered view of `selected`). \n\n`passesCorroboration` iterates over `allLines` for every content word of the candidate — it is O(words × lines) per candidate. For a 100-line document with 6 ALL_CAPS candidates of 3 words each, that is ~18 × 100 = 1800 string comparisons per call, so ~3600 total when both call sites fire on the same candidates.\n\nMore importantly, the logic is inconsistent between the two call sites:\n\n- Pre-threshold (line 1210): removes a candidate from the threshold calculation only if `≥2` ALL_CAPS remain after removal. This is a safety net — it prevents false removal.\n- Multi-title (line 1399): filters `corroboratedCaps` and falls back to `allCapsSelected` when fewer than 2 remain. Also a safety net, but the two thresholds for \"how many must remain\" are equivalent — both require `≥2`.\n\nThis is not redundant in behaviour because the two call sites operate on different arrays (`scoredForThreshold` vs. `selected`, which has already been through dedup and other filters). But the corroboration result for the same `(text, position, lines)` triple will be identical, so the second call computes something that was already computed.\n\n**Solution** — cache results after the first call:\n\n```typescript\n// After the first corroboration filter block (line 1219):\nconst corroborationCache = new Map<string, boolean>();\nfunction passesCorroborationCached(text: string, position: number, lines: string[]): boolean {\n  const key = `${position}:${text}`;\n  if (!corroborationCache.has(key)) {\n    corroborationCache.set(key, passesCorroboration(text, position, lines));\n  }\n  return corroborationCache.get(key)!;\n}\n```\n\nOr simpler: build the cache inline using the result already computed in the first block and re-use it in the second. At minimum, document why two call sites are intentional.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. Fix 4 (first-after-preamble bonus) was implemented more completely than planned — with one divergence\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1017–1055`\n\nThe plan specified two things:\n1. Make the preamble check include `isSectionLabel(trimmed)` as an additional \"treated as filtered\" condition.\n2. Increase the bonus from +0.08 to +0.12 when the preamble contained structural markers (not only empty lines), and cap combined positional boost at +0.15.\n\nWhat was implemented:\n\n- Point 1 is at line 1029: `return trimmed === \"\" || !passesHardFilters(trimmed) || isSectionLabel(trimmed);` — correct.\n- Point 2: the `hasStructuralPreamble` branch (lines 1034–1040) uses `preambleBonus = 0.12` vs `0.08`. Correct.\n- The +0.15 cap was implemented (lines 1046–1055). Correct and an improvement over the plan.\n\nOne divergence from the plan: the plan suggested making the two bonuses \"partially exclusive — if both apply, cap their combined contribution at +0.15.\" The implementation caps `totalPositionalBoost = firstCandidate.score - baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses`, which includes the structural bonus too (line 1008 shows `baseScore = rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`). But `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses = firstCandidate.baseScore` at line 1023, meaning the cap is applied after the structural bonus has already been added to `score`. This could mean the +0.10 structural bonus is already included in `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses`, so the cap actually allows `rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus + 0.15` for the first candidate — which exceeds the plan's intended maximum. This is a subtle accounting issue worth verifying.\n\n---\n\n### 4. `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` omits multi-word entries that exist in `SECTION_LABELS`\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:173–183`\n\nThe caps-coalescing merge relaxation at lines 585–587 has this guard:\n\n```typescript\nwordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\nisCategorySectionLabel(next.text)\n```\n\nThe `wordCount(next.text) === 1` guard means multi-word category labels like `\"main courses\"`, `\"fish & seafood\"`, `\"side dishes\"` can never trigger the relaxation path regardless. So their absence from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` is currently harmless for the merge logic. However, it is still a correctness gap in the set itself, and a future caller of `isCategorySectionLabel` that does not check word count first would silently get wrong answers for those multi-word entries.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `extractContentWords` silently drops words shorter than 3 alpha chars, with no comment\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:231–236`\n\n```typescript\nfunction extractContentWords(text: string): string[] {\n  return text\n    .split(/\\s+/)\n    .filter((w) => w.replace(/[^a-zA-ZÀ-ÿ]/g, \"\").length >= 3)\n    .map((w) => w.toUpperCase());\n}\n```\n\nThe threshold of `>= 3` alpha chars means a title like `\"Cod with Roe\"` yields `[\"COD\", \"WITH\", \"ROE\"]` — `\"Cod\"` (3), `\"With\"` (4), `\"Roe\"` (3) all pass — but `\"Pi z Jabłkiem\"` (a Polish title) would include `\"PIZ\"` (3 alpha after stripping `\"z\"`) and exclude `\"Z\"` (1 alpha, a preposition). The comment at line 230 says \"≥3 alpha characters after stripping punctuation\" which is correct, but there is no comment explaining why this threshold was chosen. Given that `passesCorroboration` depends on this function for its 100%/67% thresholds, the filtering choice directly affects corroboration accuracy. At minimum, a comment explaining the intent (\"short words like prepositions are not distinctive enough to distinguish titles from body text\") would help future maintainers understand why lowering this threshold would cause false negatives.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Style\n\n### 6. `isBodyProse` is placed between `looksLikeCookingInstruction` and `isTitleAbsentPage` — good, but the JSDoc omits the false-positive risk\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:355–362`\n\nPlacement is logical: the three functions form a functional group used by `isTitleAbsentPage`. The JSDoc at lines 355–358 accurately describes the check. What's missing is the documented caveat from the improvement plan: a recipe starting with a lowercase-first instruction (`\"add the onions...\"`) that has fewer than 4 words would not match `isBodyProse` — which is intentional and correct (the 4-word guard prevents short fragments from triggering this), but a reader might wonder why 4 is the threshold. The plan noted \"lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator\" but the 4-word minimum is the real guard against single-word or 3-word lowercase false matches. A brief inline comment would make this explicit.\n\n---\n\n### 7. `isCategorySectionLabel` duplicates the normalization logic from `isSectionLabel` verbatim\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:185–188` and `190–197`\n\nBoth functions contain:\n\n```typescript\nconst normalized = stripDiacritics(text.trim().replace(/[:.]$/, \"\").toLowerCase());\n```\n\nThere is no shared helper for this normalization. `isSectionLabel` also applies an OCR variant check (`l` → `i`), which `isCategorySectionLabel` does not. This is intentional — category label matching does not need OCR repair — but the divergence is not documented. If someone adds OCR resilience to `isSectionLabel` in a future iteration (e.g., handling `Í` → `I`), they would need to remember to update `isCategorySectionLabel` too, or the two functions would diverge silently. Extract the base normalization into a shared `normalizeLabelText(text: string): string` helper used by both.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Plan section \"No changes to multi-title assembly logic\" was not fully honoured\n\nThe improvement plan's \"No changes to\" list (line 369 of the plan) explicitly includes \"Multi-title assembly logic.\" The pre-threshold artifact filter (lines 1200–1219) and the corroboration call inside multi-title assembly (lines 1394–1405) are both new in iteration 26, and both alter multi-title assembly behaviour. This is not a code quality problem — the changes are correct and well-guarded — but it is a documentation accuracy issue. The plan was drafted before implementation and the implementation correctly went further than planned. Worth noting in the iteration 27 plan retrospective so the pattern (\"plan understates actual change scope\") is visible to future reviewers.\n\n---\n\n## Plan Coverage Verification\n\n| Plan Fix | Pattern | Implemented | Notes |\n|----------|---------|-------------|-------|\n| Fix 1: Expand food dictionary with common title words | B, C | Yes — `food-dictionary.ts:133–145` | ~30 words added vs. ~50 planned; `smażony`/`pieczony` diacritics variant dropped in favour of stripped forms `smazone`/`pieczone`; functionally equivalent since `repairOcrWord` normalizes via `stripDiacritics` before lookup |\n| Fix 2: Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations | E | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:585–587` | Uses `isCategorySectionLabel` instead of the plain `isSectionLabel` word-count guard from the plan; more precise because it targets category labels specifically |\n| Fix 3: Improve `findBurstEnd` spillover skip | A | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:436–471` | All three termination conditions from the plan (2+ blank lines, separator, ALL_CAPS heading) implemented |\n| Fix 4: Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus | D | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:1017–1055` | More complete than planned: includes structural-preamble detection for +0.12 vs +0.08, and adds the +0.15 combined cap |\n| Fix 5a: Unicode fractions in `startsWithNumber` | F | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:101–104` | Matches plan exactly |\n| Fix 5b: Body-prose detection in `isTitleAbsentPage` | F | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:355–381` | New `isBodyProse` function matches plan design |\n\nOne dictionary gap relative to the plan: `smażony` (with diacritic) was listed in the plan's `COMMON_TITLE_WORDS` example (line 108 of the plan). The implementation adds the OCR-stripped form `smazone`/`smazony` at `food-dictionary.ts:143`. Since `repairOcrWord` normalizes via `stripDiacritics` internally (line 107 of the extractor), the diacritic form would anyway be stripped to `smazony` before the dictionary lookup. This means the plan's diacritic forms and the implementation's stripped forms are functionally equivalent. No gap in behaviour, but the inconsistency between the plan's `smażony` and the code's `smazony` is worth noting for traceability.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `findBurstEnd` overflow-skip logic (lines 436–471) is well-structured: all three termination conditions are clearly separated, the \"don't skip past the heading itself\" guard at line 462 is correct, and the walk-to-end fallback at line 469 prevents the loop from failing silently when no terminator is found.\n- The caps-coalescing merge condition (lines 581–590) is compact and readable despite encoding a complex three-way check. The comment block at lines 169–172 correctly explains the intent.\n- The pre-threshold artifact filter (lines 1200–1219) has a good safety net: it only removes candidates when `≥2` ALL_CAPS remain after removal, preventing false removal on single-recipe pages where a unique vocabulary is expected.\n- `passesCorroboration` has a clear, correct threshold design: short candidates (≤3 content words) require 100%, longer ones require 67%. This asymmetry correctly reflects that a 2-word title must be fully attested, while a 6-word title need not have every word in the body."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: adbc853b1ca406751 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 57751\ntool_uses: 15\nduration_ms: 141222</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"80bb29ff-3467-4b06-a8e7-a7aec63d83fa","uuid":"7cf3812c-b16e-44b3-9d29-1beb0ca5079c","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review architecture and code quality of the iteration 26 changes in the title-extractor.\n\n## Context\n- Compare against the improvement plan at tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md\n- Focus on lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts and lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts\n\n## What was changed (from git diff HEAD~1):\n\n### food-dictionary.ts\n- Added ~30 common title words to FOOD_DICTIONARY (prepositions, adjectives, Polish words)\n\n### title-extractor.ts\n- New `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` set — duplicates subset of `SECTION_LABELS`\n- New `isCategorySectionLabel()` function\n- New `extractContentWords()` + `passesCorroboration()` — vocabulary corroboration\n- New `isBodyProse()` — lowercase prose detection\n- Modified `startsWithNumber` — Unicode fractions\n- Modified `isTitleAbsentPage` — body prose detection\n- Modified `findBurstEnd` — improved spillover handling\n- Modified caps-coalescing merge condition\n- Modified first-after-preamble bonus logic\n- Added pre-threshold artifact filtering\n- Modified multi-title assembly with corroboration\n\n## Architecture & quality focus:\n1. **Duplication**: `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` overlaps significantly with `SECTION_LABELS`. Should `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` be derived from `SECTION_LABELS`? Could they drift apart?\n2. **Function placement**: Are new functions placed logically in the file?\n3. **passesCorroboration** is called in two separate places (pre-threshold ~line 1210 and multi-title ~line 1400). Is this redundant? Should it be called once and cached?\n4. **Complexity growth**: The file is already large. Do these changes push it toward needing a refactor?\n5. **Naming**: Are `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`, `passesCorroboration`, `isBodyProse`, `extractContentWords` well-named?\n6. **The improvement plan** specified 5 fixes. Were all implemented? Were any implemented differently than planned?\n\nRead the actual source files and improvement plan to verify. Return specific findings with file:line references.","agentId":"adbc853b1ca406751","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. Here is the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Title Extractor — Iteration 26 Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`)\n- Plan Coverage: 5 of 6 planned changes implemented; 1 partially implemented; 1 added beyond plan\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Low Priority / Style: 3\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAll five root-cause fixes from the improvement plan were implemented, with Fix 4 (first-after-preamble bonus) implemented more completely than planned thanks to the addition of the +0.15 cap. One significant change was added beyond the plan: the pre-threshold artifact filter using `passesCorroboration` (lines 1206–1219), which is a meaningful new behaviour that the plan explicitly marked as \"no changes to multi-title assembly logic.\" The three-set label taxonomy (`SECTION_LABELS` / `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` / `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS`) now governs the same labels from three directions, and the relationships between them are not enforced in code. This is the main structural risk.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` is manually maintained and can silently drift from `SECTION_LABELS`\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:173–183`\n\n`CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` is a hand-curated subset of the category labels inside `SECTION_LABELS`. Three sets now describe overlapping membership for the same labels:\n\n```\nSECTION_LABELS            — authoritative list of all labels\nCATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS   — subset: food-group/chapter labels only\nALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS  — subset: structural process labels only\n```\n\nThe plan asks \"should `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` be derived from `SECTION_LABELS`?\" and the answer in the code is: no, it was typed out again. Concretely:\n\n- `\"main courses\"`, `\"side dishes\"`, `\"soups & broths\"`, `\"desserts & baked goods\"`, `\"fish & seafood\"`, and `\"baked goods\"` are in `SECTION_LABELS` (line 162–166) but absent from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`.\n- `\"przetwory\"` is in `SECTION_LABELS` (line 154) but missing from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`.\n- `\"dania glowne\"` is in `SECTION_LABELS` (line 151) and absent from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` — yet its English equivalent `\"main courses\"` is also absent.\n\nIf a new category label is added to `SECTION_LABELS` it will silently fail the merge-relaxation check in the caps-coalescing loop, because `isCategorySectionLabel` only consults its own independent set.\n\n**Root cause**: The three sets should form a partition of `SECTION_LABELS`, but there is no code to enforce that. The comment at line 169–172 documents the intent but does not implement it.\n\n**Solution** — derive `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` from `SECTION_LABELS` by exclusion:\n\n```typescript\n// Structural process labels that always block merges\nconst ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS = new Set([\n  \"ingredients\", \"directions\", /* ... */\n]);\n\n// Everything in SECTION_LABELS that isn't a process label is a category label\nconst CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS = new Set(\n  [...SECTION_LABELS].filter((label) => !ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS.has(label))\n);\n```\n\nThis makes the partition explicit. The only tricky entries are the cross-over ones — `\"sos\"`, `\"ciasto\"`, `\"nadzienie\"` appear in both `SECTION_LABELS` (as structural, line 127–128) and `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS` (line 213). If you derive `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` by exclusion, those correctly end up not in the category set, which matches the intent.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `passesCorroboration` is called twice on overlapping populations — caching is absent\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1210` and `1399`\n\nThe function is called once in the pre-threshold artifact filter (lines 1206–1219) over `allCapsInScored` (which is a filtered view of `scoredForThreshold`), and again inside the multi-title assembly path (lines 1398–1400) over `allCapsSelected` (a filtered view of `selected`). \n\n`passesCorroboration` iterates over `allLines` for every content word of the candidate — it is O(words × lines) per candidate. For a 100-line document with 6 ALL_CAPS candidates of 3 words each, that is ~18 × 100 = 1800 string comparisons per call, so ~3600 total when both call sites fire on the same candidates.\n\nMore importantly, the logic is inconsistent between the two call sites:\n\n- Pre-threshold (line 1210): removes a candidate from the threshold calculation only if `≥2` ALL_CAPS remain after removal. This is a safety net — it prevents false removal.\n- Multi-title (line 1399): filters `corroboratedCaps` and falls back to `allCapsSelected` when fewer than 2 remain. Also a safety net, but the two thresholds for \"how many must remain\" are equivalent — both require `≥2`.\n\nThis is not redundant in behaviour because the two call sites operate on different arrays (`scoredForThreshold` vs. `selected`, which has already been through dedup and other filters). But the corroboration result for the same `(text, position, lines)` triple will be identical, so the second call computes something that was already computed.\n\n**Solution** — cache results after the first call:\n\n```typescript\n// After the first corroboration filter block (line 1219):\nconst corroborationCache = new Map<string, boolean>();\nfunction passesCorroborationCached(text: string, position: number, lines: string[]): boolean {\n  const key = `${position}:${text}`;\n  if (!corroborationCache.has(key)) {\n    corroborationCache.set(key, passesCorroboration(text, position, lines));\n  }\n  return corroborationCache.get(key)!;\n}\n```\n\nOr simpler: build the cache inline using the result already computed in the first block and re-use it in the second. At minimum, document why two call sites are intentional.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. Fix 4 (first-after-preamble bonus) was implemented more completely than planned — with one divergence\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1017–1055`\n\nThe plan specified two things:\n1. Make the preamble check include `isSectionLabel(trimmed)` as an additional \"treated as filtered\" condition.\n2. Increase the bonus from +0.08 to +0.12 when the preamble contained structural markers (not only empty lines), and cap combined positional boost at +0.15.\n\nWhat was implemented:\n\n- Point 1 is at line 1029: `return trimmed === \"\" || !passesHardFilters(trimmed) || isSectionLabel(trimmed);` — correct.\n- Point 2: the `hasStructuralPreamble` branch (lines 1034–1040) uses `preambleBonus = 0.12` vs `0.08`. Correct.\n- The +0.15 cap was implemented (lines 1046–1055). Correct and an improvement over the plan.\n\nOne divergence from the plan: the plan suggested making the two bonuses \"partially exclusive — if both apply, cap their combined contribution at +0.15.\" The implementation caps `totalPositionalBoost = firstCandidate.score - baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses`, which includes the structural bonus too (line 1008 shows `baseScore = rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus`). But `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses = firstCandidate.baseScore` at line 1023, meaning the cap is applied after the structural bonus has already been added to `score`. This could mean the +0.10 structural bonus is already included in `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses`, so the cap actually allows `rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus + 0.15` for the first candidate — which exceeds the plan's intended maximum. This is a subtle accounting issue worth verifying.\n\n---\n\n### 4. `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` omits multi-word entries that exist in `SECTION_LABELS`\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:173–183`\n\nThe caps-coalescing merge relaxation at lines 585–587 has this guard:\n\n```typescript\nwordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4 &&\nisCategorySectionLabel(next.text)\n```\n\nThe `wordCount(next.text) === 1` guard means multi-word category labels like `\"main courses\"`, `\"fish & seafood\"`, `\"side dishes\"` can never trigger the relaxation path regardless. So their absence from `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` is currently harmless for the merge logic. However, it is still a correctness gap in the set itself, and a future caller of `isCategorySectionLabel` that does not check word count first would silently get wrong answers for those multi-word entries.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `extractContentWords` silently drops words shorter than 3 alpha chars, with no comment\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:231–236`\n\n```typescript\nfunction extractContentWords(text: string): string[] {\n  return text\n    .split(/\\s+/)\n    .filter((w) => w.replace(/[^a-zA-ZÀ-ÿ]/g, \"\").length >= 3)\n    .map((w) => w.toUpperCase());\n}\n```\n\nThe threshold of `>= 3` alpha chars means a title like `\"Cod with Roe\"` yields `[\"COD\", \"WITH\", \"ROE\"]` — `\"Cod\"` (3), `\"With\"` (4), `\"Roe\"` (3) all pass — but `\"Pi z Jabłkiem\"` (a Polish title) would include `\"PIZ\"` (3 alpha after stripping `\"z\"`) and exclude `\"Z\"` (1 alpha, a preposition). The comment at line 230 says \"≥3 alpha characters after stripping punctuation\" which is correct, but there is no comment explaining why this threshold was chosen. Given that `passesCorroboration` depends on this function for its 100%/67% thresholds, the filtering choice directly affects corroboration accuracy. At minimum, a comment explaining the intent (\"short words like prepositions are not distinctive enough to distinguish titles from body text\") would help future maintainers understand why lowering this threshold would cause false negatives.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Style\n\n### 6. `isBodyProse` is placed between `looksLikeCookingInstruction` and `isTitleAbsentPage` — good, but the JSDoc omits the false-positive risk\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:355–362`\n\nPlacement is logical: the three functions form a functional group used by `isTitleAbsentPage`. The JSDoc at lines 355–358 accurately describes the check. What's missing is the documented caveat from the improvement plan: a recipe starting with a lowercase-first instruction (`\"add the onions...\"`) that has fewer than 4 words would not match `isBodyProse` — which is intentional and correct (the 4-word guard prevents short fragments from triggering this), but a reader might wonder why 4 is the threshold. The plan noted \"lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator\" but the 4-word minimum is the real guard against single-word or 3-word lowercase false matches. A brief inline comment would make this explicit.\n\n---\n\n### 7. `isCategorySectionLabel` duplicates the normalization logic from `isSectionLabel` verbatim\n\n**File**: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:185–188` and `190–197`\n\nBoth functions contain:\n\n```typescript\nconst normalized = stripDiacritics(text.trim().replace(/[:.]$/, \"\").toLowerCase());\n```\n\nThere is no shared helper for this normalization. `isSectionLabel` also applies an OCR variant check (`l` → `i`), which `isCategorySectionLabel` does not. This is intentional — category label matching does not need OCR repair — but the divergence is not documented. If someone adds OCR resilience to `isSectionLabel` in a future iteration (e.g., handling `Í` → `I`), they would need to remember to update `isCategorySectionLabel` too, or the two functions would diverge silently. Extract the base normalization into a shared `normalizeLabelText(text: string): string` helper used by both.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Plan section \"No changes to multi-title assembly logic\" was not fully honoured\n\nThe improvement plan's \"No changes to\" list (line 369 of the plan) explicitly includes \"Multi-title assembly logic.\" The pre-threshold artifact filter (lines 1200–1219) and the corroboration call inside multi-title assembly (lines 1394–1405) are both new in iteration 26, and both alter multi-title assembly behaviour. This is not a code quality problem — the changes are correct and well-guarded — but it is a documentation accuracy issue. The plan was drafted before implementation and the implementation correctly went further than planned. Worth noting in the iteration 27 plan retrospective so the pattern (\"plan understates actual change scope\") is visible to future reviewers.\n\n---\n\n## Plan Coverage Verification\n\n| Plan Fix | Pattern | Implemented | Notes |\n|----------|---------|-------------|-------|\n| Fix 1: Expand food dictionary with common title words | B, C | Yes — `food-dictionary.ts:133–145` | ~30 words added vs. ~50 planned; `smażony`/`pieczony` diacritics variant dropped in favour of stripped forms `smazone`/`pieczone`; functionally equivalent since `repairOcrWord` normalizes via `stripDiacritics` before lookup |\n| Fix 2: Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations | E | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:585–587` | Uses `isCategorySectionLabel` instead of the plain `isSectionLabel` word-count guard from the plan; more precise because it targets category labels specifically |\n| Fix 3: Improve `findBurstEnd` spillover skip | A | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:436–471` | All three termination conditions from the plan (2+ blank lines, separator, ALL_CAPS heading) implemented |\n| Fix 4: Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus | D | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:1017–1055` | More complete than planned: includes structural-preamble detection for +0.12 vs +0.08, and adds the +0.15 combined cap |\n| Fix 5a: Unicode fractions in `startsWithNumber` | F | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:101–104` | Matches plan exactly |\n| Fix 5b: Body-prose detection in `isTitleAbsentPage` | F | Yes — `title-extractor.ts:355–381` | New `isBodyProse` function matches plan design |\n\nOne dictionary gap relative to the plan: `smażony` (with diacritic) was listed in the plan's `COMMON_TITLE_WORDS` example (line 108 of the plan). The implementation adds the OCR-stripped form `smazone`/`smazony` at `food-dictionary.ts:143`. Since `repairOcrWord` normalizes via `stripDiacritics` internally (line 107 of the extractor), the diacritic form would anyway be stripped to `smazony` before the dictionary lookup. This means the plan's diacritic forms and the implementation's stripped forms are functionally equivalent. No gap in behaviour, but the inconsistency between the plan's `smażony` and the code's `smazony` is worth noting for traceability.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `findBurstEnd` overflow-skip logic (lines 436–471) is well-structured: all three termination conditions are clearly separated, the \"don't skip past the heading itself\" guard at line 462 is correct, and the walk-to-end fallback at line 469 prevents the loop from failing silently when no terminator is found.\n- The caps-coalescing merge condition (lines 581–590) is compact and readable despite encoding a complex three-way check. The comment block at lines 169–172 correctly explains the intent.\n- The pre-threshold artifact filter (lines 1200–1219) has a good safety net: it only removes candidates when `≥2` ALL_CAPS remain after removal, preventing false removal on single-recipe pages where a unique vocabulary is expected.\n- `passesCorroboration` has a clear, correct threshold design: short candidates (≤3 content words) require 100%, longer ones require 67%. This asymmetry correctly reflects that a 2-word title must be fully attested, while a 6-word title need not have every word in the body."}],"totalDurationMs":141222,"totalTokens":57751,"totalToolUseCount":15,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":465,"cache_read_input_tokens":53007,"output_tokens":4278,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":465},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
