eed to trace through what `repairOcrText` does with \"INGREDIENTS\" to see if that's where the issue lies. in CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS? No, so that's false too. The overall condition fails, meaning the merge should break.\n\nBut the test is still failing — the output shows `WORD ONE INGREDIENTS WORD TWO`, which suggests the issue isn't with the merge logic itself but somewhere else in the candidate generation or multi-line joining. Let me trace back through the test case to see where this output is actually coming from, since this test was passing before my recent changes.\n\nMy `remainingCaps` threshold change from `>= 2` to `>= 1` might be affecting the corroboration logic. Looking at the test data: \"WORD ONE\" has two content words, and only \"WORD\" appears elsewhere (in \"WORD TWO\"), so it fails the 100% corroboration threshold for 3 or fewer words. \"INGREDIENTS\" gets filtered out by the section label check, but I need to verify where exactly it's being removed. I'm wondering if this test was already broken before my changes. The caps-coalescing logic was modified in iteration 26, and I need to check whether the original code would have passed this test or if it was already failing. Let me trace through what the original condition was checking for section labels and word count constraints. I'm checking the entry conditions for the caps-coalescing loop — `WORD ONE` passes all the checks: it's all caps, has two words, is under 25 characters, and isn't a section label or metadata. So it enters the loop. Then on the first iteration, `INGREDIENTS` also passes the initial checks: all caps, one word, under 25 characters.\n\nBut when I check if it's a section label, it returns true, which means the negation fails and the first branch of the condition is false. Then I need to verify whether \"ingredients\" is in the category section labels set — looking through the list, it's not there, so that branch is also false.\n\nSo the merge should actually break here. But I'm