ludes multiple ALL_CAPS candidates\n- Some fail corroboration (like \"WORD ONE\")\n- `remainingCaps.length` — if only 1 remains, guard prevents removal\n- So \"WORD ONE\" stays in `scoredForThreshold`\n- Threshold is based on \"WORD ONE\"'s high score\n- \"WORD ONE\" passes threshold, wins via dedup\n\nWith my `>= 1`:\n- \"WORD ONE\" fails corroboration\n- `remainingCaps.length >= 1` — if the 3-line join passes corroboration, there's ≥1 remaining\n- \"WORD ONE\" is removed from `scoredForThreshold`\n- Threshold is now based on different candidates\n\nSo the real question is whether removing \"WORD ONE\" from the threshold calculation changes which candidates ultimately get selected. If the threshold shifts based on other high-scoring candidates like the 3-line join, then both that candidate and \"WORD ONE\" might pass the threshold and enter the dedup phase, where the shorter one would win instead. Now I'm checking which ALL_CAPS candidates actually make it into `scoredForThreshold` — \"WORD ONE\" and \"WORD TWO\" both pass the hard filters, so that's at least 2 candidates. \"WORD ONE\" only has 1 out of 2 content pieces corroborating it though.\n\n\"WORD TWO\" also fails corroboration since \"TWO\" doesn't appear anywhere else in the text. Both candidates fail the corroboration check, leaving `artifactTexts` with both words but `remainingCaps` empty. The guard condition `0 >= 2` is false, so nothing gets removed — my change to `>= 1` wouldn't affect this either. This test case must have already been broken by the original iteration 26 changes, not by anything I did.\n\nBut wait — there could be a 3-line join candidate like \"WORD ONE INGREDIENTS WORD TWO\" that's all caps. It passes the hard filters since it's not a section label or metadata. For corroboration, it hits 75% which exceeds the 67% threshold for 4+ words, so it passes. Now `allCapsInScored` includes this longer phrase alongside the two single words. With the original `>= 2` guard, the two artifacts wou